WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.829 --> 00:00:04.350
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:04.350 --> 00:00:07.890
This is a free, complete course for the CCNA.

00:00:07.890 --> 00:00:11.900
If you like these videos, please subscribe
to follow along with the series.

00:00:11.900 --> 00:00:16.770
Also, please like and leave a comment, and
share the video to help spread this free series

00:00:16.770 --> 00:00:17.850
of videos.

00:00:17.850 --> 00:00:19.650
Thanks for your help.

00:00:19.650 --> 00:00:23.039
In this video we will look at wireless network
security.

00:00:23.039 --> 00:00:30.830
Specifically, exam topic 1.11.d, encryption,
and exam topic 5.9, describe wireless security

00:00:30.830 --> 00:00:35.250
protocols, WPA, WPA2, and WPA3.

00:00:35.250 --> 00:00:39.410
You’ve probably noticed by now that there
are a lot of new concepts that you need to

00:00:39.410 --> 00:00:43.019
learn to understand wireless networks.

00:00:43.019 --> 00:00:47.610
Wireless security is no exception, and this
video will be an overview of a lot of new

00:00:47.610 --> 00:00:48.610
concepts.

00:00:48.610 --> 00:00:54.530
So, take notes and do extra research if you
have to, but make sure you have a basic understanding

00:00:54.530 --> 00:00:59.739
of the concepts introduced in this video before
you take the CCNA exam.

00:00:59.739 --> 00:01:02.150
Here’s what we’ll cover.

00:01:02.150 --> 00:01:06.260
First I’ll give a brief introduction to
wireless network security and summarize what

00:01:06.260 --> 00:01:08.830
we’ll cover later in the video.

00:01:08.830 --> 00:01:13.780
Then I’ll introduce various authentication
methods, ranging from not-so-secure methods

00:01:13.780 --> 00:01:17.610
to the most secure methods used in modern
networks.

00:01:17.610 --> 00:01:21.890
Then I’ll introduce various encryption and
integrity methods.

00:01:21.890 --> 00:01:25.960
Encryption plays a role in all kinds of networks,
but it’s especially important in wireless

00:01:25.960 --> 00:01:30.830
networks because a signal can be received
by anyone within range of the sender, not

00:01:30.830 --> 00:01:33.180
just the intended recipient.

00:01:33.180 --> 00:01:38.180
And integrity means making sure that messages
aren’t modified by any attackers while in

00:01:38.180 --> 00:01:40.020
transit.

00:01:40.020 --> 00:01:46.100
Finally we’ll look at Wi-Fi Protected Access,
WPA, which was developed by the Wi-Fi alliance

00:01:46.100 --> 00:01:50.479
to provide standard sets of wireless network
security protocols.

00:01:50.479 --> 00:01:54.490
Watch until the end of the video for a bonus
practice question from Boson Software’s

00:01:54.490 --> 00:02:01.390
ExSim for CCNA, the best practice exams for
the CCNA.

00:02:01.390 --> 00:02:04.120
As you know, security is important in all
networks.

00:02:04.120 --> 00:02:08.220
However, it’s even more essential in wireless
networks.

00:02:08.220 --> 00:02:13.051
The main reason for that is: because wireless
signals are not contained within a wire, any

00:02:13.051 --> 00:02:17.020
device within range of the signal can receive
the traffic.

00:02:17.020 --> 00:02:22.470
In wired networks, traffic is often only encrypted
when sent over an untrusted network such as

00:02:22.470 --> 00:02:23.470
the Internet.

00:02:23.470 --> 00:02:28.310
You usually don’t encrypt wired traffic
within the LAN, for example.

00:02:28.310 --> 00:02:33.010
But in wireless networks, it is very important
to encrypt traffic sent between the wireless

00:02:33.010 --> 00:02:34.180
clients and the AP.

00:02:34.180 --> 00:02:39.920
That’s because, as I said before, any device
within range of the signal can receive the

00:02:39.920 --> 00:02:44.510
traffic, but we want to ensure that only the
intended recipient or recipients can read

00:02:44.510 --> 00:02:45.510
it.

00:02:45.510 --> 00:02:51.300
So, in this video we will cover three main
concepts, authentication, encryption, and

00:02:51.300 --> 00:02:52.300
integrity.

00:02:52.300 --> 00:02:56.970
You’ve heard these terms before, but let’s
look at them from a wireless perspective.

00:02:56.970 --> 00:03:01.510
We’ll look at these in more depth later
in the video, but first here’s a quick overview

00:03:01.510 --> 00:03:03.070
of each.

00:03:03.070 --> 00:03:05.830
First, authentication.

00:03:05.830 --> 00:03:10.700
As mentioned in the previous video, all clients
must be authenticated before they can associate

00:03:10.700 --> 00:03:13.260
with an AP.

00:03:13.260 --> 00:03:18.140
Authentication just means verifying the identity
of a user and/or device.

00:03:18.140 --> 00:03:22.569
In a corporate setting, only trusted users
and devices should be given access to the

00:03:22.569 --> 00:03:23.569
network.

00:03:23.569 --> 00:03:28.790
However, a separate SSID which doesn’t have
access to the corporate network can also be

00:03:28.790 --> 00:03:31.580
provided for guest users.

00:03:31.580 --> 00:03:37.020
Those guest SSIDs have less strict authentication
requirements, and probably only give access

00:03:37.020 --> 00:03:41.810
to the Internet, not to internal company resources.

00:03:41.810 --> 00:03:47.080
Not only should the AP authenticate the identity
of clients, ideally the clients should also

00:03:47.080 --> 00:03:52.270
authenticate the AP to avoid associating with
a malicious AP.

00:03:52.270 --> 00:03:57.269
A malicious AP could trick users into associating
with it, and then it can carry out attacks

00:03:57.269 --> 00:04:00.360
such as a man-in-the-middle attack.

00:04:00.360 --> 00:04:05.250
There are multiple ways that authentication
can be carried out, for example with a password,

00:04:05.250 --> 00:04:12.190
a username and password combination, or with
digital certificates installed on the devices.

00:04:12.190 --> 00:04:17.310
For review, remember that before associating
with an AP, the client must first go through

00:04:17.310 --> 00:04:19.650
an authentication process like this.

00:04:19.650 --> 00:04:24.749
Okay, we’ll look at authentication in more
detail soon but let’s introduce the next

00:04:24.749 --> 00:04:28.050
concept.

00:04:28.050 --> 00:04:30.150
Next is encryption.

00:04:30.150 --> 00:04:35.349
Traffic sent between clients and APs, so any
wireless traffic, should be encrypted so that

00:04:35.349 --> 00:04:39.729
it can’t be read by anyone except the AP
and the client.

00:04:39.729 --> 00:04:44.009
You should know this already, but encryption
means scrambling up the message so that only

00:04:44.009 --> 00:04:47.910
the sender and the intended recipient can
read it.

00:04:47.910 --> 00:04:51.840
There are many possible protocols that can
be used to encrypt traffic.

00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:56.849
It’s important that the sender and recipient
use the same protocol, or else it would be

00:04:56.849 --> 00:04:59.389
like they are speaking different languages.

00:04:59.389 --> 00:05:04.110
The recipient wouldn’t be able to decrypt
the sender’s messages.

00:05:04.110 --> 00:05:08.980
Note that all devices on the wireless LAN
will use the same encryption protocol, however

00:05:08.980 --> 00:05:13.949
each client will use a unique encryption and
decryption key so that other devices can’t

00:05:13.949 --> 00:05:16.020
read its traffic.

00:05:16.020 --> 00:05:20.720
Only the AP will have the appropriate key
to decrypt the client’s traffic, the other

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:25.080
clients won’t be able to decrypt it because
they are using different keys.

00:05:25.080 --> 00:05:29.550
However there is also a ‘group key’ which
is used by the AP to encrypt traffic it wants

00:05:29.550 --> 00:05:32.180
to send to all of its clients.

00:05:32.180 --> 00:05:36.689
All of those clients keep a copy of that group
key so they can decrypt the traffic.

00:05:36.689 --> 00:05:41.560
Again, we’ll look at wireless encryption
methods in greater detail soon, but before

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:47.240
that let’s introduce the final concept,
integrity.

00:05:47.240 --> 00:05:51.509
As explained in the security fundamentals
video of the course, integrity ensures that

00:05:51.509 --> 00:05:55.680
a message is not modified by a third party,
it is not modified in-transit.

00:05:55.680 --> 00:06:00.939
So, the message that is sent by the source
host should be the same as the message that

00:06:00.939 --> 00:06:04.080
is received by the destination host.

00:06:04.080 --> 00:06:10.120
To ensure that, a MIC, message integrity check,
is added to messages to help protect their

00:06:10.120 --> 00:06:11.479
integrity.

00:06:11.479 --> 00:06:16.330
To demonstrate how it works, let’s say the
PC on the left is a client of the AP on the

00:06:16.330 --> 00:06:17.330
right.

00:06:17.330 --> 00:06:23.139
First, the sender calculates a MIC for the
message and attaches it to the message.

00:06:23.139 --> 00:06:27.039
Just like encryption, there are many different
protocols that can be used to calculate this

00:06:27.039 --> 00:06:31.490
MIC, and it’s important that the sender
and receiver use the same protocol.

00:06:31.490 --> 00:06:36.789
Then the sender encrypts the message and MIC,
and sends the frame.

00:06:36.789 --> 00:06:41.930
The recipient decrypts the message, and then
independently calculates a MIC for the message,

00:06:41.930 --> 00:06:44.710
using the same protocol as the sender.

00:06:44.710 --> 00:06:49.639
It compares the two MICs, and if the MIC calculated
by the sender and the MIC calculated by the

00:06:49.639 --> 00:06:55.240
recipient are the same, the recipient assumes
the message wasn’t tampered with.

00:06:55.240 --> 00:06:58.909
Note that if the two MICs aren’t the same,
if they are different, the message will be

00:06:58.909 --> 00:06:59.909
discarded.

00:06:59.909 --> 00:07:05.029
So, instead of saying a MIC helps to protect
the integrity of messages, it could be more

00:07:05.029 --> 00:07:09.900
accurate to say that it helps to identify
if the integrity of a message has been compromised

00:07:09.900 --> 00:07:11.249
or not.

00:07:11.249 --> 00:07:15.159
If the integrity has been compromised, the
message will be discarded.

00:07:15.159 --> 00:07:20.830
Now let’s move on to look at various wireless
authentication methods.

00:07:20.830 --> 00:07:25.909
This will just be an overview of various authentication
methods, we won’t be going in depth.

00:07:25.909 --> 00:07:28.289
However, we will be covering a lot of them.

00:07:28.289 --> 00:07:31.289
Here they are, 7 different methods.

00:07:31.289 --> 00:07:34.659
The good news is you don’t need know to
any of them in depth.

00:07:34.659 --> 00:07:37.370
Just a basic understanding of each is fine.

00:07:37.370 --> 00:07:39.249
But make sure you take notes.

00:07:39.249 --> 00:07:44.190
Even though you only need a basic understanding,
it can be easy to mix up these different authentication

00:07:44.190 --> 00:07:47.189
methods when first learning them.

00:07:47.189 --> 00:07:52.300
The original 802.11 standard included two
options for authentication.

00:07:52.300 --> 00:07:55.969
The first one is open authentication, which
is very simple.

00:07:55.969 --> 00:08:00.400
The client sends an authentication request,
and the AP accepts it.

00:08:00.400 --> 00:08:03.379
No questions asked, no credentials required.

00:08:03.379 --> 00:08:07.039
So, this is clearly not a secure authentication
method.

00:08:07.039 --> 00:08:10.189
The AP just accepts all authentication requests.

00:08:10.189 --> 00:08:16.000
However, it is still used today in combination
with other authentication methods.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.689
After the client is authenticated and associated
with the AP, it’s possible to require the

00:08:20.689 --> 00:08:26.050
user to authenticate via other methods before
access to the network is granted.

00:08:26.050 --> 00:08:29.619
Think about Starbucks WiFi, or other public
WiFi.

00:08:29.619 --> 00:08:34.470
You might be free to associate your device
with the AP without even entering a password,

00:08:34.470 --> 00:08:40.460
but then you are probably required to login
via a web page or something like that to authenticate.

00:08:40.460 --> 00:08:44.890
After that authentication, your device is
granted access to the Internet.

00:08:44.890 --> 00:08:50.020
So, open authentication itself is not secure
at all, but it can be combined with other

00:08:50.020 --> 00:08:51.910
methods.

00:08:51.910 --> 00:08:58.320
Then the second method in the 802.11 standard
is WEP, wired equivalent privacy.

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:03.330
Actually WEP is not just an authentication
method, it provides encryption too.

00:09:03.330 --> 00:09:06.890
For encryption, it uses the RC4 algorithm.

00:09:06.890 --> 00:09:11.770
If you’re curious about RC4 try reading
on Wikipedia, but for the CCNA I recommend

00:09:11.770 --> 00:09:14.210
just knowing its name.

00:09:14.210 --> 00:09:19.050
WEP is a shared-key protocol, it requires
the sender and receiver to have the same key,

00:09:19.050 --> 00:09:21.150
a shared key.

00:09:21.150 --> 00:09:26.400
Those WEP keys can be 40 bits or 104 bits
in length.

00:09:26.400 --> 00:09:31.140
However those above keys are combined with
a 24-bit initialization vector to bring the

00:09:31.140 --> 00:09:34.700
total length to 64 bits or 128 bits.

00:09:34.700 --> 00:09:39.380
Again, read up on wikipedia if you’re curious
about the purpose of an initialization vector,

00:09:39.380 --> 00:09:42.530
but you don’t have to know it for the CCNA.

00:09:42.530 --> 00:09:48.830
Now, usually longer key lengths are more secure,
but WEP is NOT secure and can be easily cracked,

00:09:48.830 --> 00:09:50.840
regardless of the key length.

00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:54.220
You definitely should not use WEP on modern
wireless networks.

00:09:54.220 --> 00:09:59.680
So, that’s WEP encryption, but how can WEP
be used to authenticate a device?

00:09:59.680 --> 00:10:01.400
Here’s how it goes.

00:10:01.400 --> 00:10:05.130
First, the AP sends a ‘challenge phrase’.

00:10:05.130 --> 00:10:09.070
This is just a series of bits, the actual
contents don’t matter.

00:10:09.070 --> 00:10:14.440
The client then encrypts the challenge phrase
using the WEP key and sends it back.

00:10:14.440 --> 00:10:19.000
Finally the AP takes the client’s encrypted
challenge phrase and compares it to the AP’s

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:20.610
own encrypted challenge phrase.

00:10:20.610 --> 00:10:26.140
If they match, it means the AP and client
used the same key to encrypt the phrase, so

00:10:26.140 --> 00:10:28.540
the authentication is successful.

00:10:28.540 --> 00:10:34.000
Basically, the AP is just testing if the client
knows the shared key or not.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:38.310
Note that WEP can be used just to provide
encryption, or to provide both encryption

00:10:38.310 --> 00:10:40.440
and authentication.

00:10:40.440 --> 00:10:45.640
If WEP authentication is not used, open authentication
will be used and WEP will only be used for

00:10:45.640 --> 00:10:46.660
encryption.

00:10:46.660 --> 00:10:53.210
Okay, I just covered the first two options
for authentication, Open and WEP.

00:10:53.210 --> 00:10:58.160
However, open authentication on its own is
not secure, and WEP is definitely not secure

00:10:58.160 --> 00:11:01.540
either as an encryption method or an authentication
method.

00:11:01.540 --> 00:11:04.870
So, new wireless authentication methods were
needed.

00:11:04.870 --> 00:11:10.230
Now let’s look at those more secure methods,
the different variations of EAP, extensible

00:11:10.230 --> 00:11:12.230
authentication protocol.

00:11:12.230 --> 00:11:17.260
EAP itself isn’t a single authentication
protocol, but rather a framework which many

00:11:17.260 --> 00:11:25.580
other protocols, called EAP methods, are based
on, such LEAP, EAP-FAST, etc.

00:11:25.580 --> 00:11:28.730
So, what is EAP?

00:11:28.730 --> 00:11:31.100
It is an authentication framework.

00:11:31.100 --> 00:11:35.930
It defines a standard set of authentication
functions that are used by the various EAP

00:11:35.930 --> 00:11:36.930
methods.

00:11:36.930 --> 00:11:44.930
We will look at four of those methods: LEAP,
EAP-FAST, PEAP, and EAP-TLS.

00:11:44.930 --> 00:11:50.800
Note that EAP is integrated with a protocol
called 802.1X, which provides port-based network

00:11:50.800 --> 00:11:52.320
access control.

00:11:52.320 --> 00:11:54.260
Let me explain.

00:11:54.260 --> 00:12:00.180
802.1X is used to limit network access for
clients connected to a LAN or wireless LAN

00:12:00.180 --> 00:12:02.200
until they authenticate.

00:12:02.200 --> 00:12:04.570
Here are some specifics.

00:12:04.570 --> 00:12:07.070
There are three main entities in 802.1X.

00:12:07.070 --> 00:12:09.820
First, the supplicant.

00:12:09.820 --> 00:12:13.470
This is the device that wants to connect to
the network.

00:12:13.470 --> 00:12:15.460
Then there is the authenticator.

00:12:15.460 --> 00:12:18.250
This is the device that provides access to
the network.

00:12:18.250 --> 00:12:21.340
Finally, the authentication server.

00:12:21.340 --> 00:12:26.910
This is the device that receives client credentials
and permits or denies access.

00:12:26.910 --> 00:12:33.190
802.1X is used in all kinds of networks, both
wired and wireless, so you definitely should

00:12:33.190 --> 00:12:39.710
know these three definitions, supplicant,
authenticator, and authentication server.

00:12:39.710 --> 00:12:44.200
In an 802.11 wireless LAN, the supplicant
is the client that wants to connect to the

00:12:44.200 --> 00:12:47.400
network, for example a laptop.

00:12:47.400 --> 00:12:52.710
The authenticator is the device that provides
access to the network, the access point.

00:12:52.710 --> 00:12:56.880
But actually, in a split-MAC architecture
it’s the wireless LAN controller that manages

00:12:56.880 --> 00:13:00.640
the authentication, not the AP itself.

00:13:00.640 --> 00:13:03.670
And the authentication server is usually a
RADIUS server.

00:13:03.670 --> 00:13:06.470
So, here’s how it works.

00:13:06.470 --> 00:13:13.390
The 802.11 wireless authentication required
to associate with the AP is simply open authentication.

00:13:13.390 --> 00:13:15.060
Now the client is associated.

00:13:15.060 --> 00:13:19.290
However, it does not yet have full access
to the network.

00:13:19.290 --> 00:13:24.620
The only traffic allowed from the client is
traffic required for EAP authentication.

00:13:24.620 --> 00:13:28.750
And it is the authentication server that will
check the client’s credentials and decide

00:13:28.750 --> 00:13:32.420
to permit access or deny access to the network.

00:13:32.420 --> 00:13:37.710
So, the WLC is now a middle-man in the authentication
process.

00:13:37.710 --> 00:13:42.900
The 802.11 authentication required to simply
associate with the AP is open, but then there

00:13:42.900 --> 00:13:48.120
is the additional step of EAP authentication
that is required to get access to the network.

00:13:48.120 --> 00:13:54.960
So, let’s look at some different EAP authentication
methods used in wireless LANs.

00:13:54.960 --> 00:13:58.460
The first is LEAP, lightweight EAP.

00:13:58.460 --> 00:14:01.560
It was developed by Cisco as an improvement
over WEP.

00:14:01.560 --> 00:14:03.590
Here’s how it works.

00:14:03.590 --> 00:14:07.680
Clients must provide a username and password
to authenticate.

00:14:07.680 --> 00:14:12.860
But in addition to that, mutual authentication
is provided by both the client and server

00:14:12.860 --> 00:14:14.850
sending a challenge phrase to each other.

00:14:14.850 --> 00:14:21.620
In WEP, only the server sent a challenge phrase,
but in LEAP both client and server send challenge

00:14:21.620 --> 00:14:22.620
phrases.

00:14:22.620 --> 00:14:28.760
So, first challenge phrases are exchanged,
then each device encrypts the other’s challenge

00:14:28.760 --> 00:14:33.670
phrase and sends it back, and they use that
to authenticate each other like in WEP.

00:14:33.670 --> 00:14:38.480
To further improve the security, dynamic WEP
keys are used.

00:14:38.480 --> 00:14:42.590
These are WEP keys that automatically change
over time, to make it harder to crack the

00:14:42.590 --> 00:14:43.740
encryption.

00:14:43.740 --> 00:14:49.730
However, like WEP, LEAP is considered vulnerable
and should not be used anymore.

00:14:49.730 --> 00:14:54.390
Instead, you should use one of the next methods.

00:14:54.390 --> 00:15:00.760
The next method is EAP-FAST, EAP flexible
authentication via secure tunneling.

00:15:00.760 --> 00:15:02.910
This was also developed by Cisco.

00:15:02.910 --> 00:15:05.500
It consists of three phases.

00:15:05.500 --> 00:15:11.060
First, a PAC, protected access credential,
is generated and passed from the server to

00:15:11.060 --> 00:15:12.060
the client.

00:15:12.060 --> 00:15:13.540
Like this.

00:15:13.540 --> 00:15:18.870
This PAC is like a shared key and is used
in the next phase, to establish a secure TLS

00:15:18.870 --> 00:15:22.290
tunnel between the client and authentication
server.

00:15:22.290 --> 00:15:28.790
So, now there is a secure tunnel established
that can be used for secure encrypted communications.

00:15:28.790 --> 00:15:32.720
The final step is that the client is authenticated
within the TLS tunnel.

00:15:32.720 --> 00:15:34.339
Okay, that’s EAP-FAST.

00:15:34.339 --> 00:15:42.920
The last two methods are similar to EAP-FAST,
but different in some key ways.

00:15:42.920 --> 00:15:46.500
Next is PEAP, protected EAP.

00:15:46.500 --> 00:15:52.740
Like EAP-FAST, it involves establishing a
secure TLS tunnel between the client and server.

00:15:52.740 --> 00:15:56.690
But instead of a PAC, the server has a digital
certificate.

00:15:56.690 --> 00:16:01.710
It will show its digital certificate to the
client, and the client uses this to authenticate

00:16:01.710 --> 00:16:03.370
the server.

00:16:03.370 --> 00:16:07.400
This certificate is also used to establish
the secure TLS tunnel.

00:16:07.400 --> 00:16:12.480
And because only the server provides a certificate
for authentication, the client must still

00:16:12.480 --> 00:16:15.730
be authenticated within the secure tunnel.

00:16:15.730 --> 00:16:21.880
One protocol that can be used for that authentication
is called MS-CHAP, Microsoft Challenge Handshake

00:16:21.880 --> 00:16:23.870
Authentication Protocol.

00:16:23.870 --> 00:16:26.480
So, that’s PEAP.

00:16:26.480 --> 00:16:32.980
Remember that EAP-FAST uses a PAC, but PEAP
uses a digital certificate.

00:16:32.980 --> 00:16:36.830
However both involve establishing a secure
tunnel and then authenticating the client

00:16:36.830 --> 00:16:40.560
inside of that tunnel.

00:16:40.560 --> 00:16:46.920
And finally the last authentication method
is EAP-TLS, EAP transport layer security.

00:16:46.920 --> 00:16:53.810
Whereas PEAP only requires the AS, authentication
server, to have a certificate, EAP-TLS requires

00:16:53.810 --> 00:16:57.560
a certificate on the AS and on every single
client.

00:16:57.560 --> 00:17:02.839
It is considered the most secure authentication
method, but it is more difficult to implement

00:17:02.839 --> 00:17:07.490
than PEAP because every client device needs
a certificate.

00:17:07.490 --> 00:17:10.709
That can add a lot of complexity, time, and
effort.

00:17:10.709 --> 00:17:15.741
Because the client and server authenticate
each other with digital certificates, there

00:17:15.741 --> 00:17:19.119
is no need to authenticate the client within
the TLS tunnel.

00:17:19.119 --> 00:17:24.799
However, the TLS tunnel is still used to exchange
encryption key information, and we will be

00:17:24.799 --> 00:17:28.009
talking about different encryption methods
next.

00:17:28.009 --> 00:17:35.230
To summarize, EAP-TLS is the most secure authentication
method, but it takes more effort to implement,

00:17:35.230 --> 00:17:39.470
so many enterprises might prefer PEAP instead.

00:17:39.470 --> 00:17:45.010
So, those are the authentication methods you
should be aware of for the CCNA.

00:17:45.010 --> 00:17:49.110
To really understand these protocols you will
need a lot more information than I gave you

00:17:49.110 --> 00:17:50.799
in this section.

00:17:50.799 --> 00:17:56.130
But the goal of this video is just to give
an overview, not to get deep into the details.

00:17:56.130 --> 00:18:01.929
And remember, authentication refers to verifying
the identity of a device or user.

00:18:01.929 --> 00:18:05.789
Although I did mention encryption throughout
this section, in the next section we will

00:18:05.789 --> 00:18:11.190
talk about specific encryption methods used
to keep data private and secure.

00:18:11.190 --> 00:18:17.100
So, these are the encryption methods, in addition
to integrity methods, we will discuss.

00:18:17.100 --> 00:18:20.399
TKIP, CCMP, and GCMP.

00:18:20.399 --> 00:18:26.649
We could include WEP in this list too, but
I already mentioned it in the previous section.

00:18:26.649 --> 00:18:31.379
As I said before, encryption of wireless traffic
is absolutely essential, so make sure you

00:18:31.379 --> 00:18:35.769
have a basic understanding of these encryption
methods.

00:18:35.769 --> 00:18:39.019
First up, TKIP, temporal key integrity protocol.

00:18:39.019 --> 00:18:44.490
As I said before, WEP was found to be vulnerable,
however wireless hardware at the time was

00:18:44.490 --> 00:18:46.080
developed to use WEP.

00:18:46.080 --> 00:18:51.139
So, a temporary solution based on WEP was
needed until a new standard was created and

00:18:51.139 --> 00:18:53.190
new hardware was built.

00:18:53.190 --> 00:18:55.400
That temporary solution was TKIP.

00:18:55.400 --> 00:18:58.919
It’s based on WEP but adds various security
features.

00:18:58.919 --> 00:19:03.999
Now, I’m going to give you a list here but
I don’t think you need to memorize it.

00:19:03.999 --> 00:19:07.809
Just understand that TKIP is like a more secure
version of WEP.

00:19:07.809 --> 00:19:12.740
So, TKIP uses a MIC to protect the integrity
of messages.

00:19:12.740 --> 00:19:16.840
Hopefully you remember what a MIC is from
earlier in the video.

00:19:16.840 --> 00:19:22.279
Also a key mixing algorithm is used to create
a unique WEP key for every frame, instead

00:19:22.279 --> 00:19:24.650
of each frame using the same key.

00:19:24.650 --> 00:19:27.759
This makes it harder to crack the encryption.

00:19:27.759 --> 00:19:33.809
The initialization vector, which I mentioned
earlier, is doubled from 24 bits to 48 bits,

00:19:33.809 --> 00:19:38.460
which makes brute-force attacks to crack the
encryption much more difficult.

00:19:38.460 --> 00:19:44.330
The MIC includes the sender MAC address, used
to prove the identity of the frame’s sender.

00:19:44.330 --> 00:19:49.210
Also a timestamp is added, so attackers can’t
do a replay attack.

00:19:49.210 --> 00:19:53.139
Replay attacks involve re-sending frames that
have already been sent.

00:19:53.139 --> 00:19:56.770
Check wikipedia if you want to get an overview
of replay attacks.

00:19:56.770 --> 00:20:03.230
Similarly, a TKIP sequence number keeps track
of frames sent from a source MAC address.

00:20:03.230 --> 00:20:08.330
This also protects against replay attacks,
because a frame will be dropped if the sequence

00:20:08.330 --> 00:20:09.919
counter is incorrect.

00:20:09.919 --> 00:20:14.809
As I said, you probably don’t have to memorize
all of the above features.

00:20:14.809 --> 00:20:19.890
Just know that TKIP was developed as a more-secure
temporary solution after WEP was found to

00:20:19.890 --> 00:20:21.480
be vulnerable.

00:20:21.480 --> 00:20:27.419
And know that TKIP is used in WPA, WiFi Protected
Access version 1, which will be discussed

00:20:27.419 --> 00:20:30.840
in the next section.

00:20:30.840 --> 00:20:35.360
Next up is CCMP, counter/CBC-MAC protocol.

00:20:35.360 --> 00:20:39.090
It was developed after TKIP and is more secure.

00:20:39.090 --> 00:20:45.150
It is used in WPA2, and again I will explain
WPA in the next section.

00:20:45.150 --> 00:20:50.539
Note that for a device to use CCMP, it must
be supported by the device’s hardware.

00:20:50.539 --> 00:20:56.370
Old hardware built only to use WEP or TKIP
cannot use CCMP.

00:20:56.370 --> 00:21:01.039
It consists of two different algorithms to
provide encryption and a message integrity

00:21:01.039 --> 00:21:02.499
check.

00:21:02.499 --> 00:21:05.600
For encryption, it uses AES counter mode.

00:21:05.600 --> 00:21:10.860
AES is the most secure encryption protocol
currently available and is used all over the

00:21:10.860 --> 00:21:14.639
world by corporations, governments, etc.

00:21:14.639 --> 00:21:20.360
There are multiple modes of operation for
AES, and CCMP uses what’s called ‘counter

00:21:20.360 --> 00:21:23.769
mode’ because it offers high performance,
high speed.

00:21:23.769 --> 00:21:30.519
Then it uses CBC-MAC, cipher block chaining
message authentication code, as a message

00:21:30.519 --> 00:21:34.470
integrity check to ensure the integrity of
messages.

00:21:34.470 --> 00:21:39.110
You don’t have to know exactly how CBC-MAC
works, just know that it’s a kind of MIC.

00:21:39.110 --> 00:21:45.419
So, that’s how CCMP provides encryption
and integrity.

00:21:45.419 --> 00:21:49.580
Finally there is GCMP, galois counter mode
protocol.

00:21:49.580 --> 00:21:54.440
It is more secure and more efficient than
CCMP, and its efficiency allows higher data

00:21:54.440 --> 00:21:57.259
throughput than CCMP.

00:21:57.259 --> 00:22:00.980
It is used in WiFi Protected Access 3.

00:22:00.980 --> 00:22:04.049
Like CCMP, it consists of two algorithms.

00:22:04.049 --> 00:22:07.409
First, AES counter mode encryption.

00:22:07.409 --> 00:22:12.460
And then GMAC, Galois Message Authentication
Code which is used as a MIC to ensure the

00:22:12.460 --> 00:22:14.090
integrity of messages.

00:22:14.090 --> 00:22:20.259
Again, don’t worry about exactly how GMAC
works, just know that it’s a kind of MIC.

00:22:20.259 --> 00:22:23.869
So, those are the encryption methods you need
to know.

00:22:23.869 --> 00:22:29.120
Again, remember that I also introduced WEP
earlier and it is used for encryption also.

00:22:29.120 --> 00:22:33.059
I’ve added some basic notes about each protocol
below.

00:22:33.059 --> 00:22:37.299
So far we’ve covered a lot of different
authentication and encryption methods.

00:22:37.299 --> 00:22:41.570
Make sure you have taken notes on each and
know their similarities and differences.

00:22:41.570 --> 00:22:47.009
Now, with so many different authentication,
encryption, and integrity methods, which ones

00:22:47.009 --> 00:22:48.480
should we choose?

00:22:48.480 --> 00:22:51.529
Which combinations work together and which
don’t?

00:22:51.529 --> 00:22:54.549
And how can we know which hardware supports
which standards?

00:22:54.549 --> 00:22:59.809
To simplify things and create standard sets
of protocols to be used, the WiFi alliance

00:22:59.809 --> 00:23:05.279
developed the WPA, WiFi Protected Access,
industry certifications.

00:23:05.279 --> 00:23:08.850
Let’s look at WPA now.

00:23:08.850 --> 00:23:15.549
The Wi-Fi alliance has developed three WPA
certifications for wireless devices, WPA,

00:23:15.549 --> 00:23:18.710
WPA2, and WPA3.

00:23:18.710 --> 00:23:23.340
Note that the first one is just called WPA,
not WPA1.

00:23:23.340 --> 00:23:28.960
For a device to be WPA certified, it must
be tested in authorized testing labs.

00:23:28.960 --> 00:23:35.190
This is just like how the Wi-Fi alliance certifies
devices for WiFi4, WiFi 5, WiFi 6, etc.

00:23:35.190 --> 00:23:41.320
They also certify devices for WPA, WPA2, and
WPA3 security.

00:23:41.320 --> 00:23:45.609
All three of the WPAs support two different
authentication modes.

00:23:45.609 --> 00:23:51.619
First is personal mode, in which a pre-shared
key, PSK, is used for authentication.

00:23:51.619 --> 00:23:57.340
For example, when you connect to a home wifi
network, enter the password and are authenticated,

00:23:57.340 --> 00:23:58.720
that is personal mode.

00:23:58.720 --> 00:24:03.009
It’s common in small networks, such as SOHO
networks.

00:24:03.009 --> 00:24:08.320
Note that for security purposes, the PSK itself
isn’t actually sent over the air.

00:24:08.320 --> 00:24:14.559
A four-way handshake is used for the authentication,
and the PSK is used to generate encryption

00:24:14.559 --> 00:24:15.690
keys.

00:24:15.690 --> 00:24:20.039
If the devices use the same PSK to generate
the encryption keys, they will be able to

00:24:20.039 --> 00:24:24.230
decrypt each other’s traffic, meaning that
they will know that the other device is using

00:24:24.230 --> 00:24:26.669
the same PSK.

00:24:26.669 --> 00:24:30.049
In addition to personal mode, there is enterprise
mode.

00:24:30.049 --> 00:24:35.059
This is the mode that uses 802.1X with an
authentication server.

00:24:35.059 --> 00:24:40.330
I introduced a few EAP methods and they are
used with enterprise mode, although WPA doesn’t

00:24:40.330 --> 00:24:42.389
specify any specific method.

00:24:42.389 --> 00:24:47.460
So, all EAP methods are supported, such as
PEAP or EAP-TLS.

00:24:47.460 --> 00:24:53.809
Now let’s look at WPA, WPA2, and WPA3.

00:24:53.809 --> 00:24:58.730
The first WPA certification was developed
after WEP was proven to be vulnerable and

00:24:58.730 --> 00:25:01.100
it includes the following protocols.

00:25:01.100 --> 00:25:07.090
TKIP, which as you know is based on WEP, provides
encryption and integrity.

00:25:07.090 --> 00:25:13.269
Authentication can be provided by 802.1X and
EAP, when using enterprise mode, or by PSK

00:25:13.269 --> 00:25:15.370
when using personal mode.

00:25:15.370 --> 00:25:18.269
But WPA didn’t last very long.

00:25:18.269 --> 00:25:23.450
After more secure protocols and hardware were
developed, WPA2 was released and it includes

00:25:23.450 --> 00:25:25.739
the following protocols.

00:25:25.739 --> 00:25:29.409
CCMP is used to provide encryption and MIC.

00:25:29.409 --> 00:25:36.240
And again, authentication can be done via
802.1X using EAP or PSK.

00:25:36.240 --> 00:25:39.769
And finally in 2018 WPA3 was released.

00:25:39.769 --> 00:25:44.010
It uses GCMP for encryption and integrity.

00:25:44.010 --> 00:25:49.340
And once again supports 802.1X based or PSK
based authentication.

00:25:49.340 --> 00:25:55.840
In addition to that, it offers several additional
security features, here are a few examples.

00:25:55.840 --> 00:25:59.879
There is a feature called PMF, protected management
frames.

00:25:59.879 --> 00:26:05.330
It protects 802.11 management frames from
eavesdropping and forging.

00:26:05.330 --> 00:26:11.940
Actually this was available as an optional
feature in WPA2, but WPA3 makes it mandatory.

00:26:11.940 --> 00:26:16.789
Also, SAE, simultaneous authentication of
equals.

00:26:16.789 --> 00:26:20.749
It protects the four-way handshake when using
personal mode authentication.

00:26:20.749 --> 00:26:24.999
The last example I’ll give is forward secrecy.

00:26:24.999 --> 00:26:30.120
It prevents data from being decrypted after
it has been transmitted over the air.

00:26:30.120 --> 00:26:34.440
This protects against attacks in which an
attacker captures wireless frames, and then

00:26:34.440 --> 00:26:37.080
tries to decrypt them later to read the contents.

00:26:37.080 --> 00:26:41.190
Okay, that’s all I’ll say about the WPA
certifications.

00:26:41.190 --> 00:26:46.690
Basically, they take the various security
protocols I mentioned in this video, and package

00:26:46.690 --> 00:26:49.779
those protocols into standard sets.

00:26:49.779 --> 00:26:54.039
Hardware is then tested and certified to make
sure it supports these standards.

00:26:54.039 --> 00:26:57.570
Okay, here’s what we covered in this video.

00:26:57.570 --> 00:27:01.820
I’d say the content of this video was quite
wide but shallow.

00:27:01.820 --> 00:27:06.100
You got a general overview of a lot of different
security features.

00:27:06.100 --> 00:27:14.549
Make sure you know the difference between
PEAP and EAP-TLS, or CCMP and GCMP, for example.

00:27:14.549 --> 00:27:20.659
Also know which protocols are included in
WPA, WPA2, and WPA3.

00:27:20.659 --> 00:27:24.549
And make sure to watch until the end of the
quiz for a bonus practice question from Boson

00:27:24.549 --> 00:27:29.600
Software’s ExSim for CCNA, the best practice
exams for the CCNA.

00:27:29.600 --> 00:27:35.080
Now let’s go to quiz question 1.

00:27:35.080 --> 00:27:38.679
What does GMAC provide to a secure wireless
connection?

00:27:38.679 --> 00:27:42.990
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:27:42.990 --> 00:27:49.869
Okay, the best answer is B, MIC, message integrity
check.

00:27:49.869 --> 00:27:56.250
GMAC is used as part of the GCMP protocol
to verify message integrity as a message integrity

00:27:56.250 --> 00:27:57.609
check.

00:27:57.609 --> 00:28:00.600
GCMP is part of the WPA3 certification.

00:28:00.600 --> 00:28:06.009
Okay, let’s go to quiz question 2.

00:28:06.009 --> 00:28:10.070
Which of the following are part of the 802.1X
authentication architecture?

00:28:10.070 --> 00:28:19.109
(select three) Okay, pause the video now to
select the best answers.

00:28:19.109 --> 00:28:21.350
The answers are A, supplicant.

00:28:21.350 --> 00:28:25.479
D, authenticator, and E, authentication server.

00:28:25.479 --> 00:28:31.210
These are the three entities involved in 802.1X
authentication.

00:28:31.210 --> 00:28:36.990
In an 802.11 wireless network, the wireless
client is the supplicant, the AP or WLC is

00:28:36.990 --> 00:28:42.379
the authenticator, and a server such as a
RADIUS server acts as the authentication server.

00:28:42.379 --> 00:28:47.019
Okay, let’s go to question 3.

00:28:47.019 --> 00:28:51.710
Which of the following encryption and integrity
methods is considered most secure?

00:28:51.710 --> 00:28:56.249
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:28:56.249 --> 00:29:02.359
Okay, the answer is C, GCMP.

00:29:02.359 --> 00:29:09.330
These protocols were developed in the order
WEP, TKIP, CCMP, and then GCMP, and GCMP is

00:29:09.330 --> 00:29:11.119
the most secure.

00:29:11.119 --> 00:29:15.279
If your hardware supports it, it is recommended
to use GCMP whenever possible.

00:29:15.279 --> 00:29:19.700
Okay, let’s go to question 4.

00:29:19.700 --> 00:29:24.120
Which of the following AES methods requires
a certificate on both the supplicant and the

00:29:24.120 --> 00:29:25.440
AS?

00:29:25.440 --> 00:29:29.289
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:29:29.289 --> 00:29:34.980
Okay, the answer is D, EAP-TLS.

00:29:34.980 --> 00:29:42.239
Both PEAP and EAP-TLS involve digital certificates
for authentication, but PEAP only requires

00:29:42.239 --> 00:29:44.519
that the AS has a certificate.

00:29:44.519 --> 00:29:50.470
EAP-TLS, on the other, uses certificates to
authenticate both the supplicant and the AS,

00:29:50.470 --> 00:29:52.059
so they both need a certificate.

00:29:52.059 --> 00:29:57.809
Okay, let’s go to question 5.

00:29:57.809 --> 00:30:02.869
Which of the following WPA3 security features
protects the four-way handshake when using

00:30:02.869 --> 00:30:05.249
personal mode authentication?

00:30:05.249 --> 00:30:09.320
Pause the video now to select the best answer.

00:30:09.320 --> 00:30:14.039
Okay, the answer is A, SAE.

00:30:14.039 --> 00:30:20.399
SAE is simultaneous authentication of equals,
and it allows for a more secure four-way handshake

00:30:20.399 --> 00:30:22.700
during authentication using personal mode.

00:30:22.700 --> 00:30:24.759
Okay, that’s all for the quiz.

00:30:24.759 --> 00:30:32.967
Now let’s try a bonus question from Boson
Software’s ExSim for CCNA, the best practice exams for the CCNA.

